WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:02.500
All right, thank you very much.

00:00:02.500 --> 00:00:04.220
Very happy to be here.

00:00:04.220 --> 00:00:06.860
And it's a tough act to follow, but let's try.

00:00:07.720 --> 00:00:10.420
So I'm gonna tell you a little bit

00:00:10.420 --> 00:00:13.200
about some of my inspirations going into this project

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:14.700
that I'm calling Help from AI.

00:00:14.700 --> 00:00:16.740
And I'll read this paragraph to you.

00:00:16.740 --> 00:00:18.520
A Microsoft study finds,

00:00:18.520 --> 00:00:20.620
a key irony of automation is that

00:00:20.620 --> 00:00:22.379
by mechanizing routine tasks

00:00:22.379 --> 00:00:25.139
and leaving exception handling to the human user,

00:00:25.139 --> 00:00:27.719
you deprive the user of routine opportunities

00:00:27.719 --> 00:00:29.400
to practice their judgment

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:31.980
and strengthen their cognitive musculature,

00:00:31.980 --> 00:00:34.099
leaving them atrophied and unprepared

00:00:34.099 --> 00:00:36.160
when the exceptions do arise.

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:40.560
Set aside the SAT words, I agree with this statement.

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:43.779
And as a teacher of introductory data science,

00:00:43.779 --> 00:00:47.500
I feel like this is actually a lot of where I live.

00:00:47.500 --> 00:00:51.700
And I don't want these tasks offloaded necessarily.

00:00:51.700 --> 00:00:54.459
The other inspiration was this tweet by an author

00:00:54.459 --> 00:00:56.939
I don't actually know, but I agree with the sentiment.

00:00:56.939 --> 00:00:58.060
You know what the biggest problem

00:00:58.060 --> 00:01:00.020
with pushing all things AI is?

00:01:00.020 --> 00:01:00.939
Wrong direction.

00:01:00.939 --> 00:01:03.540
I want AI to do my laundry and dishes

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:05.459
so that I can do art and writing,

00:01:05.459 --> 00:01:07.879
not for AI to do my art and writing

00:01:07.879 --> 00:01:10.339
so that I can do my laundry and dishes.

00:01:10.339 --> 00:01:14.339
My laundry and dishes as a teacher is grading, I think.

00:01:14.339 --> 00:01:16.099
Needs to be done and is important,

00:01:16.099 --> 00:01:20.959
but you know, not as fun as art.

00:01:20.959 --> 00:01:23.879
So this is me thinking about,

00:01:25.220 --> 00:01:27.000
so there are certain conversations

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.639
that I really don't like having, R or Python.

00:01:29.639 --> 00:01:32.080
I also really don't like having conversations

00:01:32.080 --> 00:01:34.639
like how can we stop cheating with AI?

00:01:34.639 --> 00:01:37.959
That is not where I wanna spend my brain energy.

00:01:37.959 --> 00:01:40.800
So what I've been thinking about over the last year

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:43.279
is how can AI support student learning

00:01:43.279 --> 00:01:46.160
instead of help them take shortcuts in their learning?

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:49.419
And I myself as an educator also love to learn.

00:01:49.419 --> 00:01:51.720
So I figured I need to interact with these things

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:53.959
a little bit myself, maybe programmatically

00:01:53.959 --> 00:01:56.559
more than just type things into a chat bot

00:01:57.080 --> 00:01:58.639
and see where we can get within a year.

00:01:58.639 --> 00:02:01.080
So this is a story of that.

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:04.400
As a context, I teach an introductory data science course.

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:07.080
It is a large course, at least large for my institution.

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:08.600
I have 300 students.

00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:10.259
I have TA support.

00:02:10.259 --> 00:02:12.399
Many of them are undergraduate TAs

00:02:12.399 --> 00:02:13.839
who have just taken the course,

00:02:13.839 --> 00:02:17.100
so super helpful, super good with the students,

00:02:17.100 --> 00:02:19.339
but don't always have sort of the big picture

00:02:19.339 --> 00:02:21.520
just established in their head yet.

00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:24.360
And in terms of what we cover in the course,

00:02:24.360 --> 00:02:27.000
it is most of R for data science,

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.839
sort of beginning of tidy modeling with R,

00:02:29.839 --> 00:02:32.000
and a lot from my textbook introduction

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:33.000
to modern statistics.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:35.199
So there's a lot of interpreting results

00:02:35.199 --> 00:02:37.839
as well as using code to get to results.

00:02:37.839 --> 00:02:39.660
And in terms of the technology,

00:02:39.660 --> 00:02:42.600
students are learning to code in R in RStudio.

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:45.460
Every single thing is a Corto document,

00:02:45.460 --> 00:02:46.839
and every single assignment

00:02:46.839 --> 00:02:49.020
is submitted as a GitHub repository.

00:02:50.100 --> 00:02:53.199
Now, the AI policy that I set last year

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:55.440
was that you can use it for code,

00:02:55.440 --> 00:02:58.960
and here is some information on how to cite it properly.

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:01.639
You can't use it to generate narrative.

00:03:01.639 --> 00:03:03.559
Unless instructed otherwise,

00:03:03.559 --> 00:03:05.919
you must come up with your own narrative.

00:03:05.919 --> 00:03:07.520
And you can use it for learning,

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:11.639
but don't believe everything it says, in longer words.

00:03:11.639 --> 00:03:14.279
I think that was a little too optimistic.

00:03:14.279 --> 00:03:17.520
To be perfectly honest, I haven't necessarily changed this,

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:20.559
but I use that opportunity of the learning

00:03:20.559 --> 00:03:24.080
throughout last year to sort of figure out

00:03:24.080 --> 00:03:26.880
like where do we go next from here.

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:30.679
So the first project, I will admit, a little uninspired,

00:03:30.679 --> 00:03:33.039
because no one really needs another chatbot,

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:35.080
but we started here.

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:37.440
The thing about the chatbot is that it is one

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:41.000
that hopefully generates good, helpful, and correct answers

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:43.039
that come from course content.

00:03:43.039 --> 00:03:44.600
That's the important piece,

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:47.440
and prefers terminology, syntax, methodology,

00:03:47.440 --> 00:03:50.320
and workflows that are taught in the course.

00:03:51.080 --> 00:03:52.919
In terms of the technical details,

00:03:52.919 --> 00:03:57.320
in the back end, we're working with open source models,

00:03:57.320 --> 00:04:00.559
but then using RAG to build a knowledge graph,

00:04:00.559 --> 00:04:04.039
a searchable, traversable graph of a database

00:04:04.039 --> 00:04:05.880
from the course textbooks,

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:09.160
and also using semantic similarity search.

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:12.600
I'll give you an example of what this looks like in a second.

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:14.759
And so we're using these tools to figure out

00:04:14.759 --> 00:04:16.640
when a student asks a question,

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:19.920
where in the materials could the answers be?

00:04:20.519 --> 00:04:21.839
So we embedded this chatbot

00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:24.359
in the Canvas learning management system,

00:04:24.359 --> 00:04:27.799
which is what our university uses,

00:04:27.799 --> 00:04:30.119
which is like where things go to die, unfortunately,

00:04:30.119 --> 00:04:32.279
but we had to embed it somewhere

00:04:32.279 --> 00:04:34.640
that is not necessarily publicly accessible,

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:38.160
because one of the other motivations behind this project

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:41.480
was that I don't want how far a student can go

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:43.279
using AI tools to be limited

00:04:43.279 --> 00:04:46.040
by their credit card limit either.

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:48.480
So we wanted to make sure that students enrolled

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:53.480
can have access to the same level of using the AI tool.

00:04:54.839 --> 00:04:56.720
So this is what it looks like.

00:04:56.720 --> 00:04:58.440
Let's say you ask a question,

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:00.760
it thinks about it a little bit,

00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:05.279
and then gives you some answer, generally okay answers.

00:05:05.279 --> 00:05:07.880
But importantly, you can see on the side,

00:05:07.880 --> 00:05:11.600
we have page numbers to course textbooks,

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:13.679
and then it actually opens up,

00:05:13.679 --> 00:05:15.720
I'm gonna track back a little bit,

00:05:15.720 --> 00:05:18.200
a page from the open intro statistics book.

00:05:18.880 --> 00:05:21.880
So the idea being that if a student is constantly

00:05:21.880 --> 00:05:24.320
being shot to the same area in the book,

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:26.000
maybe they will pause and say,

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:28.519
maybe I'll just read this chapter

00:05:28.519 --> 00:05:30.679
instead of constantly asking questions.

00:05:30.679 --> 00:05:34.040
Let's ask another question that's more of an R question,

00:05:34.040 --> 00:05:37.160
and here they're going to get sent

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:39.440
to the sort of the right page

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:41.760
in R for data science as well.

00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:45.399
By making this link sort of immediate for students,

00:05:45.399 --> 00:05:48.920
my hope was that they can come back to student content.

00:05:48.920 --> 00:05:52.200
So the chat bot itself is not adding a whole lot

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:54.480
to what we have around us,

00:05:54.480 --> 00:05:57.480
but hopefully this immediate linking is.

00:05:57.480 --> 00:06:01.200
And we were able to track students' questions.

00:06:01.200 --> 00:06:02.440
These were all being sort of like

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:04.839
written to a backend anonymously,

00:06:04.839 --> 00:06:08.079
so I was able to sort of analyze the data over the summer.

00:06:08.079 --> 00:06:10.160
And we saw that students were using this,

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:12.119
but not many of them were using it,

00:06:12.119 --> 00:06:14.320
but it was helpful as a proof of concept

00:06:14.320 --> 00:06:15.839
for like, we can build this thing,

00:06:15.839 --> 00:06:19.279
and we can let students make calls to this thing.

00:06:19.279 --> 00:06:22.600
So come the next project that I think is,

00:06:22.600 --> 00:06:24.640
at least for me, a little more inspired,

00:06:24.640 --> 00:06:26.959
a little bit different than what I've seen out there,

00:06:26.959 --> 00:06:29.119
and something that I've enjoyed working on,

00:06:29.119 --> 00:06:31.559
and now I can say that my students

00:06:31.559 --> 00:06:32.880
have sort of enjoyed it as well,

00:06:32.880 --> 00:06:35.040
so I'll share some details about that.

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:37.119
So this was a feedback bot that, again,

00:06:37.119 --> 00:06:40.440
hopefully generates good, helpful, and correct feedback

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:43.399
based on an instructor-designed rubric,

00:06:43.399 --> 00:06:46.239
and suggests terminology, syntax, methodology,

00:06:46.239 --> 00:06:48.559
and workflows taught in the course.

00:06:48.559 --> 00:06:50.880
I want to underscore the word feedback.

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:52.640
I am not talking about grading,

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:55.480
and I am not talking about assigning scores here.

00:06:55.480 --> 00:06:58.679
We're talking about giving immediate feedback to students.

00:06:59.600 --> 00:07:02.959
Now, let's talk a little bit about motivations.

00:07:02.959 --> 00:07:04.959
I talked about, I mentioned a couple things

00:07:04.959 --> 00:07:05.839
I don't like saying.

00:07:05.839 --> 00:07:08.239
I also really don't like the word disrupt

00:07:08.239 --> 00:07:10.239
in anything related to tech and education,

00:07:10.239 --> 00:07:11.679
but I was like, this is my call.

00:07:11.679 --> 00:07:14.000
This is my opportunity to do it.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:15.839
There's an increasing number of students

00:07:15.839 --> 00:07:18.720
who use AI tools as a first step

00:07:18.720 --> 00:07:21.239
before thinking about how to approach a task.

00:07:21.239 --> 00:07:25.440
So my goal was to say, can I just wiggle my way in there

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:28.600
between the time that a student reads an exercise

00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:31.480
and the first line of code that they write?

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:35.320
Leveraging, I already have to write

00:07:35.320 --> 00:07:37.640
really meticulous rubric items.

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:40.720
My university uses Gradescope, which if you've used it,

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:43.519
you have to have well-defined rubric items.

00:07:43.519 --> 00:07:46.279
And I have a large number of TAs

00:07:46.279 --> 00:07:48.079
with varying experience levels,

00:07:48.079 --> 00:07:50.440
grading a large number of students' work,

00:07:50.440 --> 00:07:53.119
so I need to make sure that they are sticking

00:07:53.119 --> 00:07:55.160
to a very well-defined rubric.

00:07:55.160 --> 00:07:58.720
And these are a pain to write, to be perfectly honest,

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:01.720
but that work is already getting done no matter what,

00:08:01.720 --> 00:08:05.559
so I've been thinking, how else can we leverage this?

00:08:05.559 --> 00:08:08.000
And also, hopefully, shifting resources.

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:12.480
Could AI also help TAs redistribute their time a little bit

00:08:12.480 --> 00:08:15.720
towards higher value and more enjoyable for them

00:08:15.720 --> 00:08:17.600
touch points with students?

00:08:17.600 --> 00:08:21.320
And away from repetitive and error-prone tasks,

00:08:21.320 --> 00:08:24.040
which is grading, most of which go unread.

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:26.359
Because guess what happens when the homework

00:08:26.359 --> 00:08:28.440
is done mostly by AI?

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:30.720
No one reads the feedback because they're like,

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:32.479
well, I don't know, I don't actually know

00:08:32.479 --> 00:08:34.280
what's in there in the first place.

00:08:34.280 --> 00:08:36.559
So now, a week after I turn this in,

00:08:36.559 --> 00:08:38.880
why would I read the feedback written for me?

00:08:39.919 --> 00:08:41.440
And self-care.

00:08:41.440 --> 00:08:45.200
Neither the TAs nor I want to provide detailed feedback

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:48.280
to answers generated solely with AI tools.

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:51.359
And solely is the word I wanna underscore there.

00:08:51.359 --> 00:08:54.000
This is not about discouraging people

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:55.799
from using the AI tools.

00:08:55.799 --> 00:08:56.880
I use them myself.

00:08:56.880 --> 00:08:59.840
It would be very hypocritical for me to say you can't,

00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:02.559
but to be copying and pasting

00:09:02.559 --> 00:09:05.080
the first answer ChatGPT gives you,

00:09:05.080 --> 00:09:07.000
and then for another human to spend time

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:08.760
giving feedback to that just doesn't seem

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:11.159
like a good use of resources.

00:09:11.159 --> 00:09:12.119
Or mental health.

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:16.280
So the technical details is that we have a tool

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:20.960
that uses prompt engineering to ground the feedback bot

00:09:20.960 --> 00:09:24.280
with a question, some rubrics, and an answer.

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:27.520
This is a shortened version of the call using Elmer,

00:09:27.520 --> 00:09:31.359
but I tried to make it fit into a slide.

00:09:31.359 --> 00:09:33.760
So we have a system prompt that basically says

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:35.320
you're a helpful course instructor

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:37.280
teaching a course on data science

00:09:37.280 --> 00:09:38.960
with the R programming language

00:09:38.960 --> 00:09:41.760
and tidyverse and tidymodels suite of packages.

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:44.760
You give succinct but precise feedback.

00:09:44.760 --> 00:09:48.400
And we feed the bot with the question,

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:52.119
a detailed rubric that even has the answer key in it

00:09:52.119 --> 00:09:54.400
that takes the student's answer

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:57.440
and compares it against this detailed rubric,

00:09:57.440 --> 00:10:00.359
but then writes a feedback back to the student

00:10:00.359 --> 00:10:01.919
using a much simpler rubric

00:10:01.919 --> 00:10:04.799
so that the feedback doesn't just have the answer.

00:10:04.799 --> 00:10:07.880
So it doesn't say answer should be 30 instead of 60.

00:10:07.880 --> 00:10:10.599
It just says something that hopefully nudges the students

00:10:10.599 --> 00:10:11.760
in the right direction.

00:10:13.320 --> 00:10:14.919
I'll give you a demo.

00:10:14.919 --> 00:10:18.320
The TLDR of the question is make a box plot

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:20.760
and identify outliers from the data.

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:22.760
And this is what the rubric looks like,

00:10:22.760 --> 00:10:24.359
but we don't have to focus on the words.

00:10:24.359 --> 00:10:26.799
The important thing is that it has bullet points.

00:10:26.799 --> 00:10:28.799
And so you can imagine that a human

00:10:28.799 --> 00:10:30.520
would go through this answer

00:10:30.520 --> 00:10:33.440
and sort of could do almost like a true false thing

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:37.400
for these rubric items is how the rubrics are designed.

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:40.159
And this is what the tool looks like.

00:10:40.159 --> 00:10:42.000
So we are in our studio.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.239
We're writing a Quarto document.

00:10:44.239 --> 00:10:47.080
The student writes their answer

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:51.080
and then they select their answer, narrative and code.

00:10:51.080 --> 00:10:54.159
And then they go and use an add-in,

00:10:54.159 --> 00:10:55.799
which looks something like this,

00:10:55.799 --> 00:10:59.159
where they need to, for now, the homework,

00:10:59.159 --> 00:11:00.960
sort of like the feeding of the backend

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:02.080
is a little hard-coded.

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:03.559
I'm saying these are the questions

00:11:03.559 --> 00:11:06.159
that correspond to this week's homework.

00:11:06.159 --> 00:11:07.000
Maybe in the future,

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:08.919
we'll make that a little more flexible.

00:11:08.919 --> 00:11:11.080
But the student chooses the homework number

00:11:11.080 --> 00:11:12.679
and the question number.

00:11:12.679 --> 00:11:15.000
And you can see that they can't type other things

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:16.679
to the chat box right now.

00:11:16.679 --> 00:11:19.799
It is whatever that comes from their Quarto document

00:11:19.799 --> 00:11:23.679
that I am hoping means they rendered, it actually worked,

00:11:23.679 --> 00:11:27.080
like they feel good about it to begin with.

00:11:27.080 --> 00:11:28.919
And then they say, get feedback.

00:11:29.679 --> 00:11:30.599
It thinks for a little bit,

00:11:30.599 --> 00:11:33.000
and then it gives some feedback.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:34.880
And the feedback looks something like this.

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:38.119
The bolded text is those rubric items that we saw,

00:11:38.119 --> 00:11:40.520
that we fed it from the simple rubric.

00:11:40.520 --> 00:11:44.760
Each one of them has some succinct narrative

00:11:44.760 --> 00:11:45.640
that goes with it,

00:11:45.640 --> 00:11:48.799
which is more than a human could do in this course

00:11:48.799 --> 00:11:50.679
for every single rubric item.

00:11:50.679 --> 00:11:53.039
And then an overall summary as well.

00:11:53.039 --> 00:11:56.719
And note that all of this is happening in the IDE

00:11:56.719 --> 00:12:00.159
and while the student is working on the assignment.

00:12:00.159 --> 00:12:02.880
So these questions, part one of the homework

00:12:02.880 --> 00:12:04.640
is now not graded,

00:12:04.640 --> 00:12:07.080
but it is for them to practice with

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:09.640
and get experience with what their evaluation

00:12:09.640 --> 00:12:12.440
will look like before they submit the other health

00:12:12.440 --> 00:12:14.559
to be graded by humans,

00:12:14.559 --> 00:12:18.440
which will use a similar workflow, basically.

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:21.559
Let's give another example so they can close it up.

00:12:21.559 --> 00:12:26.520
Another question, the tool works in exactly the same way.

00:12:27.280 --> 00:12:30.400
You can choose your question, ask for feedback,

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:32.520
and you can get feedback on this.

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:34.640
Now, if this was just code,

00:12:34.640 --> 00:12:37.159
obviously we wouldn't necessarily,

00:12:37.159 --> 00:12:41.119
well, we wouldn't necessarily need LLMs to do this,

00:12:41.119 --> 00:12:44.799
but note that we're giving feedback on narrative and code.

00:12:44.799 --> 00:12:47.440
So this is not something that at least I know,

00:12:47.440 --> 00:12:51.320
or even some of the best educators I know out there know,

00:12:51.320 --> 00:12:54.239
how to write like meticulous unit tests for.

00:12:54.280 --> 00:12:55.840
And the other thing is that

00:12:55.840 --> 00:12:57.719
I am not writing any sort of tests.

00:12:57.719 --> 00:12:59.880
So it's a little bit easier to update these

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:01.919
from this semester to semester,

00:13:01.919 --> 00:13:04.239
as long as I'm willing to write rubric items,

00:13:04.239 --> 00:13:06.080
which I would have to do either way.

00:13:07.359 --> 00:13:10.799
So the tool itself is a shiny app.

00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:14.919
And then you can use it as an RStudio add-in.

00:13:14.919 --> 00:13:19.039
It is out there today and you can sort of like look at it,

00:13:19.039 --> 00:13:20.359
but I will be very honest,

00:13:20.359 --> 00:13:21.960
this is a little bit antithetical

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:23.679
to those of you who might know me.

00:13:24.119 --> 00:13:26.359
I like making things very, very open,

00:13:26.359 --> 00:13:28.559
but currently this is sort of hard-coded

00:13:28.559 --> 00:13:31.760
to send to a backend that you wouldn't be able to send to,

00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:33.599
because we're hosting the model online,

00:13:33.599 --> 00:13:35.280
but the calls are there.

00:13:35.280 --> 00:13:38.200
So I'll talk a little bit about next steps

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:40.119
in terms of making it widely available,

00:13:40.119 --> 00:13:43.400
but the idea and the implementation is very borrowable.

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:45.039
Just the model we're hosting,

00:13:45.039 --> 00:13:47.039
basically Duke won't let me allow all of you

00:13:47.039 --> 00:13:49.400
to make calls to the model is what it is.

00:13:50.359 --> 00:13:53.000
So a little bit of takeaways.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:54.559
In terms of the process,

00:13:54.559 --> 00:13:58.000
it was lots of fiddling with the rubric file,

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.239
just trying and testing over and over.

00:14:00.239 --> 00:14:02.719
And it was frankly a little bit unclear

00:14:02.719 --> 00:14:04.640
or hard to measure to what end

00:14:04.640 --> 00:14:07.119
we can get the rubric items right.

00:14:07.119 --> 00:14:10.679
But separating out to rubric simple and rubric detailed,

00:14:10.679 --> 00:14:14.320
which is something I didn't do when I had human graders,

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:17.520
was really helpful for hiding the answers,

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:21.359
but still testing against the answers

00:14:21.359 --> 00:14:22.919
for each of the questions.

00:14:23.799 --> 00:14:25.239
In terms of the good,

00:14:26.200 --> 00:14:27.840
the spell out your reasoning,

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:29.960
which I had originally started with,

00:14:29.960 --> 00:14:32.200
resulted in really lengthy feedback

00:14:32.200 --> 00:14:34.440
that would be unlikely that any student

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:36.320
would be frankly willing to read.

00:14:37.239 --> 00:14:39.960
But adding word limits really helps,

00:14:39.960 --> 00:14:41.559
and they're a little bit arbitrary,

00:14:41.559 --> 00:14:44.200
but I'm sort of feeling my way through them.

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:46.320
And the nice thing is it sort of works.

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:48.919
Like this actually is helpful,

00:14:48.919 --> 00:14:51.000
and I believe the feedback that it gives me

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:52.919
about 90% of the time.

00:14:54.280 --> 00:14:57.000
Now let's talk a little bit about the bad.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
I think the most concerning is that

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:02.679
the feedback tends to catch errors, but not the good.

00:15:02.679 --> 00:15:06.000
And it seems to reiterate the rubric item

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.919
whether the item is met or not,

00:15:08.919 --> 00:15:11.479
which could sort of like frustrate the students,

00:15:11.479 --> 00:15:13.200
and I worry about that.

00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:16.000
But it's a little bit on par with an inexperienced TA,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:17.200
to be perfectly honest,

00:15:17.200 --> 00:15:20.239
who tries to do pattern matching anyway.

00:15:20.239 --> 00:15:22.599
The inevitable is the inconsistency.

00:15:22.599 --> 00:15:24.039
If you send the same answer,

00:15:24.039 --> 00:15:27.080
you don't always get the same feedback.

00:15:27.080 --> 00:15:28.039
Is this frustrating?

00:15:28.039 --> 00:15:28.880
I don't know.

00:15:28.880 --> 00:15:30.280
We'll see as the students use it more.

00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:31.919
So far they've only been able to use it

00:15:31.919 --> 00:15:33.359
for one homework in the class.

00:15:33.359 --> 00:15:35.359
The semester just started.

00:15:35.359 --> 00:15:37.119
And hallucinations do happen.

00:15:37.119 --> 00:15:39.359
Sometimes it says you haven't used the base pipe

00:15:39.359 --> 00:15:41.239
when you absolutely have.

00:15:41.239 --> 00:15:44.280
So that's something we need to sort of like work on.

00:15:44.280 --> 00:15:46.039
And then sometimes it says things

00:15:46.039 --> 00:15:47.719
that as a student would really annoy me.

00:15:47.880 --> 00:15:50.640
It's not aligning with rubric expectations.

00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:52.400
What does that mean, rubric expectations?

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:53.320
Really vague.

00:15:54.440 --> 00:15:57.479
Now the student feedback, as preliminary as it is,

00:15:57.479 --> 00:16:00.760
is that they love the immediate feedback in the IDE.

00:16:01.599 --> 00:16:04.719
They like it as a helpful quick check.

00:16:04.719 --> 00:16:05.919
They find it too picky,

00:16:05.919 --> 00:16:07.880
but then they find humans too picky as well.

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:08.719
So I don't know.

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:13.320
And they said that it's not as helpful as office hours.

00:16:13.320 --> 00:16:15.599
And I'm like, that's great, actually.

00:16:15.640 --> 00:16:18.239
Like that is exactly where I would want this to land,

00:16:18.239 --> 00:16:19.799
to be perfectly honest.

00:16:20.799 --> 00:16:24.559
And in terms of revisiting the motivations,

00:16:24.559 --> 00:16:26.960
I think we're getting in there a little bit

00:16:26.960 --> 00:16:29.400
because these are also logged.

00:16:29.400 --> 00:16:32.239
And I'm not seeing that the answers they're submitting

00:16:32.239 --> 00:16:36.239
to the tool look as generically chat GPT generated,

00:16:36.239 --> 00:16:37.320
but give me some time

00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:39.359
because those models are getting better too.

00:16:39.359 --> 00:16:41.679
So detection is hard.

00:16:41.679 --> 00:16:43.039
I think we're able to leverage

00:16:43.039 --> 00:16:44.559
the work we're already putting in.

00:16:44.559 --> 00:16:47.000
And we have been able to shift resources

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.239
for more in-person time with the TAs

00:16:49.239 --> 00:16:52.280
because they're not spending as much time grading.

00:16:52.280 --> 00:16:55.119
We'll see about part two that's being graded this week

00:16:55.119 --> 00:16:57.159
if that part is the graded part

00:16:57.159 --> 00:17:00.159
is still just mostly chat GPT or not.

00:17:00.159 --> 00:17:02.159
And in terms of the next steps,

00:17:02.159 --> 00:17:05.079
we're gonna do a little bit of model evaluation.

00:17:05.079 --> 00:17:07.880
We're gonna keep working on prompt enhancements.

00:17:07.880 --> 00:17:09.520
One thing the students requested

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:11.719
that I already had in mind was to continue

00:17:11.719 --> 00:17:14.280
because we already have the chat tool anyway.

00:17:14.959 --> 00:17:15.959
Can we, after the feedback,

00:17:15.959 --> 00:17:18.880
actually allow them to talk back and forth?

00:17:18.880 --> 00:17:21.359
So that's gonna be V2 of this app.

00:17:22.239 --> 00:17:25.119
I need to improve selection with the visual editor.

00:17:25.119 --> 00:17:27.079
It's a little bit janky right now.

00:17:27.079 --> 00:17:29.239
And I wanna work on the tool itself

00:17:29.239 --> 00:17:31.239
for sharing it more widely.

00:17:31.239 --> 00:17:34.079
And maybe one day I'll do like a proper assessment on it,

00:17:34.079 --> 00:17:37.359
but currently I'm enjoying the tool building phase.

00:17:37.359 --> 00:17:39.640
I really wanna thank my partner in crime,

00:17:39.640 --> 00:17:41.599
Mark McHale from Duco IT,

00:17:41.599 --> 00:17:43.040
who's helped with the backhand

00:17:43.040 --> 00:17:46.400
and Duco IT for letting him use his time for this.

00:17:46.400 --> 00:17:47.439
And thank you very much.

00:17:47.439 --> 00:17:49.079
I'd be happy to answer any questions.

00:17:49.079 --> 00:17:49.959
Thank you.

